
 ✅ What is Traceability Matrix?

Traceability Matrix (RTM) is a document that maps:

> Requirements ↔ Test Cases

to make sure every requirement is tested.

In simple words:

👉 It ensures nothing is missed in testing.

---

 🧠 Simple Definition (Interview Ready)

> Traceability Matrix is a document used to track requirements and ensure that all requirements are covered by test cases.

---

 🏫 Easy Analogy: Exam Syllabus vs Questions

Imagine:

 Teacher gives 10 chapters (Requirements)
 You prepare 20 questions (Test Cases)

Now you check:

 Did I prepare questions for all 10 chapters?
 Did I miss any chapter?

If Chapter 7 has no questions → You forgot to study it ❌

RTM is like that checking sheet.

---

 🏢 Real-Time Software Example

Suppose client gives 3 requirements for Login page:

| Req ID | Requirement                              |
| ------ | ---------------------------------------- |
| R1     | User should login with valid credentials |
| R2     | Show error for invalid password          |
| R3     | Password should be minimum 8 characters  |

Now you create test cases:

| TC ID | Test Case                            |
| ----- | ------------------------------------ |
| TC1   | Login with valid username & password |
| TC2   | Login with wrong password            |
| TC3   | Check password length validation     |

Now RTM will look like:

| Req ID | Requirement                | TC ID |
| ------ | -------------------------- | ----- |
| R1     | Valid login                | TC1   |
| R2     | Invalid password error     | TC2   |
| R3     | Password length validation | TC3   |

👉 This ensures all requirements are covered.

---
Good 👍 Now let’s clearly understand:

1️⃣ Requirement Traceability Matrix (RTM)
2️⃣ Defect Traceability Matrix (DTM)

Both are very important in software testing.

---

 ✅ 1️⃣ Requirement Traceability Matrix (RTM)

 🔹 Definition

> Requirement Traceability Matrix is a document that maps Requirements ↔ Test Cases to ensure all requirements are covered by testing.

---

 🧠 Easy Analogy – School Syllabus

Teacher gives 5 chapters (Requirements).
You prepare questions (Test Cases).

RTM checks:

👉 Did I prepare questions for ALL chapters?
👉 Did I miss any chapter?

If Chapter 4 has no questions → You missed testing that requirement ❌

---
Easy Analogy: Building a House

Imagine you are building a house.

Client gives requirements:

3 Bedrooms

2 Bathrooms

1 Kitchen

🧠 Think of RTM like a Construction Checklist

It checks:

👉 Did we build all 3 bedrooms?
👉 Did we build 2 bathrooms?
👉 Did we forget kitchen?

If kitchen is missing ❌ → Big problem!

So RTM ensures:

All client requirements are built and tested.

🔹 In Software

Requirement = Login should work
Test Case = Test login with valid data

RTM checks:

👉 Is login tested?
👉 Did we miss anything?

 🏢 Real-Time Example (Login Page)

 Requirements:

| Req ID | Requirement                     |
| ------ | ------------------------------- |
| R1     | Login with valid credentials    |
| R2     | Show error for invalid password |
| R3     | Password must be 8 characters   |

 Test Cases:

| TC ID | Description          |
| ----- | -------------------- |
| TC1   | Test valid login     |
| TC2   | Test wrong password  |
| TC3   | Test password length |

 RTM Table:

| Req ID | TC ID |
| ------ | ----- |
| R1     | TC1   |
| R2     | TC2   |
| R3     | TC3   |

✅ Ensures 100% coverage.

---

 🎯 Purpose of RTM

 Avoid missing requirements
 Track coverage
 Used during audits
 Helps in impact analysis

